entry.title: [A11y] Update inherited cached value changes in all descendants
entry.content:
Some cached values in AXObject are dependent on the parent value.

Therefore, when the parent value changes, the values of descendants

must also be updated. Not doing this leads to stale values, which

in turn triggers checks that enforce a clean tree after an

update, and checks that require that children are not invalidated

at an illegal time.



The general fix is that when a value changes that might be inherited,

to set a flag that indicates children need to be updated. This

recursively causes all descendants to be updated during

UpdateTreeIfNeeded().



Specifics:

1. When cached values that are inherited by descendants change, call a

common method, OnInheritedCachedValuesChanged().

2. OnInheritedCachedValuesChanged() differentiates between two cases:

A) Values are changing during a tree update, when a top to bottom sweep of the tree is occurring. In this case, flags are set to ensure the loop

propagates changes to the children of the current node. This will

recursively propagate as long as a descendant changes any inheritable

value.

B) Update occurs outside of UpdateTreeIfNeeded(). In this case, flags

are set so that the next UpdateTreeIfNeeded() will update the descendants of this node.



In both cases, a new flag called child_cached_values_need_update_ is

set to true on the current node. This ensures that when children are

added to a node, that the children all update their cached values.



Fixed: 1506895

entry.content:

HeaderView and the suggestions below in such way that part of the

space was computed for the HeaderView and part of it was carried by

the Suggestion below.

- this permits HeaderView to appropriately center vertically without

manually increasing or off-loading spacing to other suggestions,

- ensures that HeaderView works correctly with all suggestion types,

including carousel.



The initial header padding and header height now match mocks exactly:

- 40dp tall,

- 24dp start padding.



The change assumes we're launching the revamped Omnibox UI and does

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Cull per ML ranking instead of traditional ranking
entry.content:
go/autocomplete-controller-refactor has some details on the refactor

plan.



This is part 7 of the refactor.



Before this CL, autocomplete passes with transferred matches looked

like:



1. Sort, dedupe, cull, etc the new matches

2. Append the old matches to the new matches

3. ML score the merged matches

4. Sort, dedupe, cull, etc the merged matches



This was problematic, because step 1 would cull matches based on

traditional scores instead of the ML scores. So it could lead to culling

a match that's scored higher by the ML model than another match that

wasn't culled.



This didn't affect the autocomplete passes without transferred matches,

since those only do steps 3 & 4.



This CL moves ML scoring (step 3) before the initial culling (step 1):



3. ML score the new matches

2. Sort, dedupe, cull, etc the new matches

3. Append the old matches to the new matches

4. Sort, dedupe, cull, etc the merged matches



This also helps avoid overwriting the score demotions

`TransferOldMatches()` does.



This is not feature guarded, because the impact on ranking is probably

small.



Bug: 1405555

CreateSharedImage is scheduled requiring context. However

be lost (and no longer current) due to an earlier task, which can cause

crashes in CreateSharedImage. Check for context loss and skip if so;

also handle potential corner cases where SI does not exist after

CreateShaedImage.

entry.title: Merge null string and empty string cases in field_filling_utils
entry.content:
As of crrev.com/c/4988249 the logic for filling CC fields and Address

fields was decoupled. The CL was supposed to be a no-op, however there

was a slight behavioral change:



Previously, we used to retrieve a value for select elements if we find

a value to fill AND this value is not empty. After the CL, the second

condition was dropped which means that if we find a value to fill but

this value is empty (which should not happen in general, but sadly

there are many obscure hidden cases) we will now attempt to find a

valid select option.



This is problematic since some select option functions use substring

matching to find a valid option, which will return an arbitrary option

if the value is empty.



This CL strengthens the logic by making functions return empty strings

instead of null strings (dropping the optional return value) so that

those two cases become one and the same throughout the whole logic.

entry.title: When testing MPC hits for matching inherited data, compare by-value.
entry.content:
This makes for a more expensive comparison, but we get it back by

getting complete MPC hits more often -- saving both RAM and CPU.

(The effect is especially pronounced on style recalcs, where the

MPC already most likely contains nearly everything we'd want.)

In particular, if two elements get the same state from different

parts in the tree, the pointers are not the same, but the data

is equivalent. E.g.



* div

* div class="a"

* span class="b"

* div class="a"

* span class="b" <-- would get a partial MPC hit before, full now



Note also that there is a knock-on effect from reusing the ComputedStyle

from the MPC hit, in that any similar children of the two spans would

now automatically have the same group pointers for inherited data,

too (so when we get a match, we don't need the by-value comparison for

all the children; the pointers will be the same and the comparison will

short-circuit).



This saves a large amount of ComputedStyle RAM:



Video 766 → 395 kB ( -371 kB)

Extension 3002 → 1670 kB (-1332 kB)

News 1724 → 1442 kB ( -282 kB)

ECommerce 238 → 198 kB ( -40 kB)

Social1 755 → 588 kB ( -167 kB)

Social2 536 → 461 kB ( -75 kB)

Encyclopedia 1658 → 1293 kB ( -365 kB)

Sports 541 → 409 kB ( -132 kB)

Search 415 → 238 kB ( -177 kB)



It would be possible to force-rewrite equivalent pointers into

each other to save yet more RAM (one of them could be GC-ed away

even if we did not have an MPC match), but from a quick prototyping,

the effect is mostly small, and it costs a little more CPU (~1%).

entry.title: Prioritize password predictions over single username ones for saving.
entry.content:
Some forms receive both single username and password predictions.

Classifiers cannot produce such classifications, but for top websites

with many overrides deployed and multiple forms being reused for

different flows, this is possible.



Single username predictions are historically prioritized even though

they are less reliable. This leads to PasswordManager ignoring

password fields and not attempting to save values inputted by the user.

]

joined_labels = ", ".join((label for bit, label in components if x & bit))

return joined_labels if len(joined_labels) else "None"

entry.title: Make AutofillModelExecutor stateless
entry.content:
AutofillModelExecutor

- Converts tokenized field labels to TFLite tensors, which can be fed

into the field prediction ML model. (Called "preprocess")

- Converts from TFLite tensors, as output by the ML model, back to a

representation that Autofill understands. (Called "postprocess")



Consider feeding the labels of a form with n fields into the executor.

Since the ML model has a max number of fields k it can process,

preprocessing might drop some of them. In this case, the output of

postprocess will have size k.

Similarly, if n < k, preprocess doesn't discard any fields, but

postprocess makes sure that the final output has size n.

In short, the output of postprocess is currently always of size

min(n, k).



This is implemented by keeping state (namely min(n, k)) in the executor,

because the form (or rather the labels) are only available to

preprocess.

Keeping this state is awkward, because the state only makes sense if

every call to preprocess is followed by a call to postprocess/no two

model executions can happen in parallel. And this already turned out to

be wrong - see crbug.com/1514408.



Instead, let's not keep any state. This CL changes the implementation

such that the output of postprocess is always k instead of min(n, k).

It becomes the job of the consumer (which already needs to deal with the

model output size != form size case) to act accordingly.

This simplifies the implementation, since postprocess can simply return

everything that the model output.



Fixed: 1514408
